.SH NAME
AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server \- WebSocket server for AnyEvent
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&    use AnyEvent::Socket qw(tcp_server);
\&    use AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server;
\&    
\&    my $server = AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server\->new();
\&    
\&    my $tcp_server;
\&    $tcp_server = tcp_server undef, 8080, sub {
\&        my ($fh) = @_;
\&        $server\->establish($fh)\->cb(sub {
\&            my $connection = eval { shift\->recv };
\&            if($@) {
\&                warn "Invalid connection request: $@\en";
\&                close($fh);
\&                return;
\&            }
\&            $connection\->on(each_message => sub {
\&                my ($connection, $message) = @_;
\&                $connection\->send($message); ## echo
\&            });
\&            $connection\->on(finish => sub {
\&                undef $connection;
\&            });
\&        });
\&    };
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class is an implementation of the WebSocket server in an AnyEvent context.
.IP \(bu 4
Currently this module supports WebSocket protocol version 13 only. See RFC 6455 <https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6455> for detail.
.SH "CLASS METHODS"
.IX Header "CLASS METHODS"
.ie n .SS "$server = AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server\->new(%args)"
.el .SS "\f(CW$server\fP = AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server\->new(%args)"
.IX Subsection "$server = AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server->new(%args)"
The constructor.
.PP
Fields in \f(CW%args\fR are:
.ie n .IP """handshake"" => CODE (optional)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWhandshake\fR => CODE (optional)" 4
.IX Item "handshake => CODE (optional)"
A subroutine reference to customize the WebSocket handshake process.
You can use this option to validate and preprocess the handshake request and customize the handshake response.
.Sp
For each request, the handshake code is called like
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    ($response, @other_results) = $handshake\->($request, $default_response)
.Ve
.Sp
where \f(CW$request\fR is a Protocol::WebSocket::Request object,
and \f(CW$default_response\fR is a Protocol::WebSocket::Response object.
The \f(CW$handshake\fR code must return \f(CW$response\fR. \f(CW@other_results\fR are optional.
.Sp
The return value \f(CW$response\fR is the handshake response returned to the client.
It must be either a Protocol::WebSocket::Response object,
or a string of a valid HTTP response (including the Status\-Line, the Headers and the Body).
.Sp
The argument \f(CW$default_response\fR is a Protocol::WebSocket::Response valid for the given \f(CW$request\fR.
If you don\*(Aqt need to manipulate the response, just return \f(CW$default_response\fR. That is,
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    handshake => sub { $_[1] }
.Ve
.Sp
is the minimal valid code for \f(CW\*(C`handshake\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
In addition to \f(CW$response\fR, you can return \f(CW@other_results\fR if you want.
Those \f(CW@other_results\fR can be obtained later from the condition variable of \f(CWestablish()\fR method.
.Sp
If you throw an exception from \f(CW$handshake\fR code, we think you reject the \f(CW$request\fR.
In this case, the condition variable of \f(CWestablish()\fR method croaks.
.ie n .IP """validator"" => CODE (optional)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWvalidator\fR => CODE (optional)" 4
.IX Item "validator => CODE (optional)"
\&\fBThis option is only for backward compatibility. Use \fR\f(CB\*(C`handshake\*(C'\fR\fB option instead. If \fR\f(CB\*(C`handshake\*(C'\fR\fB option is specified, this option is ignored.\fR
.Sp
A subroutine reference to validate the incoming WebSocket request.
If omitted, it accepts the request.
.Sp
The validator is called like
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    @other_results = $validator\->($request)
.Ve
.Sp
where \f(CW$request\fR is a Protocol::WebSocket::Request object.
.Sp
If you reject the \f(CW$request\fR, throw an exception.
.Sp
If you accept the \f(CW$request\fR, don\*(Aqt throw any exception.
The return values of the \f(CW$validator\fR are sent to the condition variable of \f(CWestablish()\fR method.
.ie n .IP """ssl_key_file"" => FILE_PATH (optional)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWssl_key_file\fR => FILE_PATH (optional)" 4
.IX Item "ssl_key_file => FILE_PATH (optional)"
A string of the filepath to the SSL/TLS private key file in PEM format.
If you set this option, you have to set \f(CW\*(C`ssl_cert_file\*(C'\fR option, too.
.Sp
If this option or \f(CW\*(C`ssl_cert_file\*(C'\fR option is set, AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server encrypts the WebSocket streams with SSL/TLS.
.ie n .IP """ssl_cert_file"" => FILE_PATH (optional)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWssl_cert_file\fR => FILE_PATH (optional)" 4
.IX Item "ssl_cert_file => FILE_PATH (optional)"
A string of the filepath to the SSL/TLS certificate file in PEM format.
.Sp
The file may contain both the certificate and corresponding private key. In that case, \f(CW\*(C`ssl_key_file\*(C'\fR may be omitted.
.Sp
If this option is set, AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server encrypts the WebSocket streams with SSL/TLS.
.ie n .IP """max_payload_size"" => INT (optional)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWmax_payload_size\fR => INT (optional)" 4
.IX Item "max_payload_size => INT (optional)"
The maximum payload size for received frames. Currently defaults to whatever Protocol::WebSocket defaults to.
Note that payload size for sent frames are not limited.
.SH "OBJECT METHODS"
.IX Header "OBJECT METHODS"
.ie n .SS "$conn_cv = $server\->establish($fh)"
.el .SS "\f(CW$conn_cv\fP = \f(CW$server\fP\->establish($fh)"
.IX Subsection "$conn_cv = $server->establish($fh)"
Establish a WebSocket connection to a client via the given connection filehandle.
.PP
\&\f(CW$fh\fR is a filehandle for a connection socket, which is usually obtained by \f(CWtcp_server()\fR function in AnyEvent::Socket.
.PP
Return value \f(CW$conn_cv\fR is an AnyEvent condition variable.
.PP
In success, \f(CW\*(C`$conn_cv\->recv\*(C'\fR returns an AnyEvent::WebSocket::Connection object and \f(CW@other_results\fR returned by the handshake process.
In failure (e.g. the client sent a totally invalid request or your handshake process threw an exception),
\&\f(CW$conn_cv\fR will croak an error message.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    ($connection, @other_results) = eval { $conn_cv\->recv };
\&    
\&    ## or in scalar context, it returns $connection only.
\&    $connection = eval { $conn_cv\->recv };
\&    
\&    if($@) {
\&        my $error = $@;
\&        ...
\&        return;
\&    }
\&    do_something_with($connection);
.Ve
.PP
You can use \f(CW$connection\fR to send and receive data through WebSocket. See AnyEvent::WebSocket::Connection for detail.
.PP
Note that even if \f(CW$conn_cv\fR croaks, the connection socket \f(CW$fh\fR remains intact.
You can communicate with the client via \f(CW$fh\fR unless the client has already closed it.
.ie n .SS "$conn_cv = $server\->establish_psgi($psgi_env, [$fh])"
.el .SS "\f(CW$conn_cv\fP = \f(CW$server\fP\->establish_psgi($psgi_env, [$fh])"
.IX Subsection "$conn_cv = $server->establish_psgi($psgi_env, [$fh])"
The same as \f(CWestablish()\fR method except that the request is in the form of PSGI environment.
.PP
\&\f(CW$psgi_env\fR is a PSGI environment object obtained from a PSGI server.
\&\f(CW$fh\fR is the connection filehandle.
If \f(CW$fh\fR is omitted, \f(CW\*(C`$psgi_env\->{"psgix.io"}\*(C'\fR is used for the connection (see PSGI::Extensions).
.SH EXAMPLES
.IX Header "EXAMPLES"
.SS "handshake option"
.IX Subsection "handshake option"
The following server accepts WebSocket URLs such as \f(CW\*(C`ws://localhost:8080/2013/10\*(C'\fR.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    use AnyEvent::Socket qw(tcp_server);
\&    use AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server;
\&    
\&    my $server = AnyEvent::WebSocket::Server\->new(
\&        handshake => sub {
\&            my ($req, $res) = @_;
\&            ## $req is a Protocol::WebSocket::Request
\&            ## $res is a Protocol::WebSocket::Response
\&    
\&            ## validating and parsing request.
\&            my $path = $req\->resource_name;
\&            die "Invalid format" if $path !~ m{^/(\ed{4})/(\ed{2})};
\&            
\&            my ($year, $month) = ($1, $2);
\&            die "Invalid month" if $month <= 0 || $month > 12;
\&    
\&            ## setting WebSocket subprotocol in response
\&            $res\->subprotocol("mytest");
\&            
\&            return ($res, $year, $month);
\&        }
\&    );
\&    
\&    tcp_server undef, 8080, sub {
\&        my ($fh) = @_;
\&        $server\->establish($fh)\->cb(sub {
\&            my ($conn, $year, $month) = eval { shift\->recv };
\&            if($@) {
\&                my $error = $@;
\&                error_response($fh, $error);
\&                return;
\&            }
\&            $conn\->send("You are accessing YEAR = $year, MONTH = $month");
\&            $conn\->on(finish => sub { undef $conn });
\&        });
\&    };
.Ve
